channel.title: ASF JIRA
channel.description: This file is an XML representation of an issue

item.title: [PDFBOX-2007] Performance regression since PDFRenderer
item.description:
Hi,

I have the following toy project where I use PDFBox: https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj

I've been using the snapshot versions of PDFBox for quite a while and recently since the move from RenderUtil#convertToImage to PDFRenderer#renderImage (this commit: https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj/commit/47917d494f2a9a0999da7f36827c45145d4bb42c), there is quite a big performance regression. If I change the PDFBox dependency to 1.8.x, everything is good. Here are my benchmarks:

PDFBox 1.8.x:
Running 1m test @ http://127.0.0.1:8080/testing.pdf?page=1
4 threads and 4 connections
Thread Stats Avg Stdev Max +/- Stdev
Latency 208.98ms 58.27ms 391.43ms 52.08%
Req/Sec 4.63 1.73 8.00 62.88%
1224 requests in 1.00m, 72.34MB read
Requests/sec: 20.40
Transfer/sec: 1.21MB

PDFBox 2.0.0:
Running 1m test @ http://127.0.0.1:8080/testing.pdf?page=1
4 threads and 4 connections
Thread Stats Avg Stdev Max +/- Stdev
Latency 920.25ms 378.94ms 2.76s 91.38%
Req/Sec 0.80 0.40 1.00 80.17%
275 requests in 1.00m, 15.85MB read
Requests/sec: 4.58
Transfer/sec: 270.41KB

I have not looked any further than this and have no more data to give you (yet).

status.description: The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are not closed can be reopened.

comments.comment:
I assume the relevant code is
https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj/blob/master/src/taz_clj/converter.clj
Is it possible for you to do a profiling within PDFBox, i.e. to see how much time is spent in the private PDFRenderer.renderPage method, as compared to the old PDPage.convertToImage() ?

This way we could find out whether the difference is in the rendering, or in the PDFBox code before the rendering. I ask this because both were changed.

And does this happen with any PDF, or with a certain, special PDF?

Btw don't worry if the answer to the first question (profiling) is "no", I could also do it myself. But I'd really be interested in an answer the second question, i.e. what sort of PDF it is, i.e. lots of graphic, lots of text, or "doesn't matter what PDF".
Can you attach the PDF in question to this issue? (Using More > Attach Files). Otherwise we cannot reproduce your specific problem. It could be anything.

I attached the PDF used in the posted benchmark. If I remember correctly when I last tested, pretty much every PDFs were slower but this one was way worse. I am sorry for the late reply I am quite busy lately. I may eventually try profiling deeper later.
I got it
I downloaded the PDF.

Yeah, 2.0 is really really slower. 1.8 renders the image almost immediately, 2.0 needs several seconds. I found two slow operations: "Do" (Invoke named XObject, which is a DCT image here), and "Tf" (select font). I can't comment on Tf but I can comment on Do. It uses the DCTFilter. The old version just used the JPXFilter. Both use java ImageIO, the old version used a "dumb" method, the new version supports CMYK, YCbCr and YCCK jpegs and uses all sort of workarounds to bypass java bugs.

Anyway, I found one piece of code I could optimize: fromBGRtoRGB(), done in rev 1584837 for the trunk. I'm handling one pixel line instead of just one pixel. That part takes 30% of the previous time (for that method). Funny thing is that handling the whole image at a time makes it slower (60% instead of 30%). This still won't be as fast as 1.8, but it is a small start: rendering page 1 now takes 4 secs instead of 5 secs on my pc. Luckily, there are not many files with DCT encoding.

About the PDF - do you mind if I reupload it "for committers only" after you deleted it? This is just so that it is part of the record.
I just deleted the uploaded PDF. No problem that you reupload it for commiters only. Thanks for looking into it!

On my machine this file takes 3.87s for the first page with 2.0.0 compared with 2.93 using 1.8.4, which is only about 30% slower. About 1s of that time is spent in SampledImageReader#getRGBImage, which is new in 2.0.

Tilman, the old version of DCTFilter was not used for reading JPEGs in 1.8, all JPEG reading was instead performed by PDJpeg which used many of the workarounds you mention for reading CMYK, YCbCr and YCCK images.
Tilman, I'm seeing 30% of the time being spent in SampledImageReader#getRGBImage versus 4% for fromBGRtoRGB.

/DCTDecode images are being read by JPXFilter in 1.8, see PDFBOX-52.

About SampledImageReader: a few weeks ago I noticed that one optimization potential in getRGBImage() would be to check whether the source domain = destination domain = 0...255. This would save some of the math. I didn't really research this, however. (At "interpolate to domain")

No, the code in DCTDecode is never called in 1.8, PDJpeg reads the images using the following code which does not apply the DCTDecode filter:

InputStream data = getPDStream().getPartiallyFilteredStream( DCT_FILTERS );

The stream is returned with the DCT data still encoded, and is passed to ImageIO.read which reads the file using one of its "JPEG" providers.

I didn't claim that DCTDecode is called. I said that "/DCTDecode" images are being handled by JPXFilter in 1.8. See the discussion in PDFBOX-52 near the end, this was the same misunderstanding. And see this code in 1.8:

        addFilter( COSName.DCT_DECODE, jpxFilter);
        addFilter( COSName.DCT_DECODE_ABBREVIATION, jpxFilter);

What is correct is that the stream is read by ImageIO.
That's not really correct, DCTDecode images are in practice not handled by JPXFilter because that code is never called as PDJpeg skips the /DCTDecode filter by calling getPartiallyFilteredStream().
Sorry, you are correct. My theory applied only to inline images making use of DCTFilter

I tried some bechmarks, it is 3.5sec for 1.8 and 5.5sec for 2.0 at 72 dpi, which is about what you measured. I can't understand why the PDFReader app is much faster for 1.8. Maybe because it is using a different method (drawer.drawPage()).

fbernier please post the exact link for the source code for 1.8.

a few weeks ago I noticed that one optimization potential in getRGBImage() would be to check whether the source domain = destination domain = 0...255. This would save some of the math.

This was my first thought too, because it is getRGBImage() itself which is slow. I've added a fast path in revision 1584914 for 8-bit images which don't use non-default Decode arrays or color masks, i.e. the majority of images. On my machine I'm getting around 2.8s for the trunk now vs 2.6 for version 1.8

Update: I should add that getRGBImage() is now very fast, under 1% of the execution time. The remaining difference in performance between 1.8 and 2.0 is now due to fromBGRtoRGB at 5.7% of execution time and DCTFilter#decode itself at 4.5%.
Yeah!!! I'm now getting almost identical benchmarks for both versions, and yes, it is much faster.
Great, we might make some incremental improvements but this issue seems to be resolved.

Thanks for the last commits, there is definitely some improvements. However, I am still not getting on-par performances with 1.8.4. Here are the results of my latest benchmark:

Running 1m test @ http://127.0.0.1:8080/testing.pdf?page=1
4 threads and 4 connections
Thread Stats Avg Stdev Max +/- Stdev
Latency 301.70ms 57.50ms 582.06ms 70.80%
Req/Sec 2.93 0.57 4.00 70.44%
810 requests in 1.00m, 46.69MB read
Requests/sec: 13.50
Transfer/sec: 796.68KB

I will try to push a branch with the 1.8.4 dependency soon...

I'd still like to see the 1.8 code. If I understand correctly, the code I linked to will render the second page of the PDF, because the parameter is 0 based. However the second page is much easier to render.

Here is the code fixed to work on 1.8.4: https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj/tree/1.8

I am using the very first page of the PDF (index 0)

see: https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj/blob/master/src/taz_clj/converter.clj#L9

Notice the (dec ...) which decrements the passed argument.

Well, it looks like this could be the effects of multi-threading and synchronisation at work, given that our micro-benchmarks can't reproduce an effect this dramatic. Could you run a VisualVM profile against your web server and upload a screenshot of the "Hot Spots" tab?

Ok... next thing I wonder about: you're doing 800 requests / min with 4 threads. So one request would be done in 0,3 secs. I need 2-3 seconds on my computer. My computer is a few years old, but not THAT old.

You're possibly not closing the document. The 2.0 version has a higher memory footprint.

I am calling with-open which should take care of closing the document: ( https://github.com/fbernier/taz-clj/blob/master/src/taz_clj/converter.clj#L11 )

I just tried not closing it and I am getting "WARNING: Warning: You did not close a PDF Document" followed with "java.lang.NullPointerException" so I guess I would be seeing this if I was not closing it correctly.

As for the performance, well that's what I am getting in this corei7 linux laptop with a SSD.

I will be providing a VisualVM profile as soon as I can.
